# STORAGE (RAM / DISK )

Q: What is virtual memory?
virtual memory = hardware RAM + swap space
Swap 

Q: What is a ramdisk?
A virtual disk in the ram that is NEVER swapped to disk

Q: What is a tmpfs?
A ramdisk that can be swapped!

Q: What is swap?
The swap is a section of the hard disk drive that is used to swap the RAM.
SWapping occurs when the RAM is more than 80% (?) full.
Swapping = a section of the RAM is coping to the hard disk andi vice-versa
cat /proc/swaps
swapon -s
free -m
top

Q: How much disk space should be used for Swap space?
Rule of thumb:
Swap space == Equal RAM size (if RAM < 8GB)
Swap space == 0.50 times the size of RAM (if RAM > 8GB)
The reality is the amount of swap space a system needs is not really a function 
of the amount of RAM it has but rather the memory workload that is running on that system.


Q: What is shm?
/dev/shm is a good place for separate programs to communicate with each other. 
For example, one can implement a simple resource lock as a file in shared memory. 
It is fast because there is no disk access (although swap may occasionally happen). 
mount | grep shm
tmpfs on /dev/shm type tmpfs (rw,nosuid,nodev)
cd /dev/shm/   <-- it is a filesystem !!!
/dev/shm frees you up from having to implement shared memory blocks yourself. 
You get (almost) all of the advantages of a shared memory block using stdio functions. 
It also means that SIMPLE BASH SCRIPTS can use shared memory to communicate with each other.
Everything done with shm could done with a “normal” file, but would be a slower.

